<dl id="n52152f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n52" href="#n52152f">N52 (VI.B.42)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n52all.htm#n52152f"> 152(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> roquelaire <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n52152f"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Even so, it was bad enough: he was arrayed in a shabby old silk roquelaire, and there was a towel upon his breast, pinned behind his neck. 44 (Relating how, In the Watches of the Night, a Vision Came to Sturk, and his Eyes were Opened): When things arrived at this stage, and he <font color="green">[Sturk]</font> had gathered his recollections about him, and found himself capable of thinking, being a man of action, up he bounced and struck a light, vaulted into his breeches, hauled on his stockings, hustled himself into his roquelaure, and, candle in hand, in slippered feet, glided, like a ghost, down stairs to the back drawing-room, which, as we know, was his study. <small> J. Sheridan Le Fanu, <a name="HBC2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#HBC2"><cite title="source">The House by the Churchyard</cite></a> (1899) 14 (How Puddock Purged O&apos;Flaherty&apos;s Head)</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
